    "description": "The Via Nova Traiana is a Roman road built along the Limes Arabicus during the reigns of the emperors Trajan and Hadrian. The route may supersede an earlier one known as the \"Via Regia\" or \"King's Highway\", a route of communication and transhumance in use since the Neolithic period.",
    "details": "<p><em>The Barrington Atlas Directory</em> notes: Madaba → Philadelpheia; Philadelpheia → Map 69; Madaba → Petra; Betthorus → Castra Mefaa → Philadelpheia; Da'janiya → Dhat Ras; Esbous → Livias → Hierichous; Mortuum Mare → Via Nova Traiana; Mothous → Arindela; Petra region; Philadelpheia → Gerasa (Map 69). <span>For </span><em>Barrington Atlas</em><span> map 69, </span>Adra(h)a → Kapitolias; Adra(h)a → Gerasa → S; Ake → Bethsaida → Kochaba; Ake → Legio → Ginai(a) → Samaria → Khirbet et Tira; Ake → Sepphoris; Apollonia → SE; Berytus → Heliopolis; Bostra → Adra(h)a; Bostra → Gerasa; Bostra → Nelkomia; Bostra → Triacome → Mothana → S; Buraq → Dionysias; Caesarea → Gaba Philippi; Caesarea → Kapharsaba → Antipatris (Map 70); Caesarea → Legio → Scythopolis; Caesarea → Neapolis → Korea(i); Caesarea → Scythopolis via Ginai(a); coast road; Damascus → Casama; Dionysias → Canatha → Nelkomia; Dionysias → Salamanestha; el-Ghassule; Gadara → Pella → Asophon → S; Gadara → Scythopolis; Gadara → Tiberias; Heliopolis → Damascus; Heliopolis → N; Khan el-Abyad → Thelseae → Damascus → Aere → Neue → S; Nejha; Palaibyblos → Sidon → Caesarea → Apollonia; Paneas → Bethsaida; Phaine → *Airita → Dionysias → Bostra; S → Gerasa → Pella → Scythopolis; Tiberias → Bethsaida → Hippos → Sennabris Tiberias → Sepphoris → Legio; Tricomia → Umm al-Quttein → S; Tyrus → Paneas → Damascus; Via Nova Traiana → Umm al-Jimal</p>\r\n<p>The Via Nova Traiana is marked on two maps in the Barrington Atlas, namely 69 D5 and 71 B2.</p>",
